uary 1275–28 June 1346":"1275年1月8日–1346年6月28日","1275–1346":"1275年–1346年","1275–Female":"1275年–殁","1302–1362":"1302年–1362年","1255–Male":"1255年–殁","1255–Female":"1255年–殁","28 June 1346":"1346年6月28日","1302":"1302年","1346":"1346年","8 January 1275":"1275年1月8日","1255":"1255年","1275":"1275年","1362":"1362年","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"苏格兰洛包爾","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"英国諾圖波藍德赫本","lifeSummary":"当Richard le Fourbour于1275年1月8日出生在苏格兰洛包爾时，他的父亲Le Fourbour21岁，母亲le Fourbour21岁。他和le Fourbour至少有1个女儿。他去世于1346年6月28日在他的家乡享年71岁。"},"hr":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8. siječnja 1275.–28. lipnja 1346.","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–preminula","1302–1362":"1302.–1362","1255–Male":"1255–preminuo","1255–Female":"1255–preminula","28 June 1346":"28. lipnja 1346.","1302":"1302.","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8. siječnja 1275.","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England"},"cs":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8. ledna 1275–28. června 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Zesnulá","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Zesnulý","1255–Female":"1255–Zesnulá","28 June 1346":"28. června 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8. ledna 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, Anglie"},"da":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8. januar 1275–28. juni 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Afdød","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Afdød","1255–Female":"1255–Afdød","28 June 1346":"28. juni 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8. januar 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Skotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England"},"nl":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8 januari 1275–28 juni 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Overleden","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Overleden","1255–Female":"1255–Overleden","28 June 1346":"28 juni 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8 januari 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Schotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8 January 1275–28 June 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Deceased","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Deceased","1255–Female":"1255–Deceased","28 June 1346":"28 June 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8 January 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard le Fourbour was born on 8 January 1275, in Roxburghshire, Scotland, his father, Le Fourbour, was 21 and his mother, le Fourbour, was 21. He had at least 1 daughter with le Fourbour. He died on 28 June 1346, in his hometown, at the age of 71."},"et":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8. jaanuar 1275–28. juuni 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Surnud","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","28 June 1346":"28. juuni 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8. jaanuar 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8. tammikuuta 1275–28. kesäkuuta 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Kuollut","1302–1362":"1302–1362","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","28 June 1346":"28. kesäkuuta 1346","1302":"1302","1346":"1346","8 January 1275":"8. tammikuuta 1275","1255":"1255","1275":"1275","1362":"1362","Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Roxburghshire, Scotland","Hepburn, Northumberland, England":"Hepburn, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"8 January 1275–28 June 1346":"8 janvier 1275–28 juin 1346","1275–1346":"1275–1346","1275–Female":"1275–Décéd